In most cases, decrease fluorescence signals were observed, such as those under the influence from quenching or inner filtering effects [29–31]. This type of phenomenon was also observed with some fluorophores mixed with dopamine [22–26]. For the nanoclusters obtained here, a totally different response profile was rendered. The introduction of a dopamine sample at 10 μM lead to about 100% increase of the fluorescence intensity at the longer wavelength (red), while the one at 440 nm kept almost unchanged (Fig. 1
                        ). This fluorescence enhancement was so significant that under a 365-nm UV lamp, the difference could be directly recognized with naked eyes (Fig. 1). It was also noticeable that dopamine lead to the position of the peak at longer wavelength moved from 580 nm to 600 nm. The provided an effective means for the detection of dopamine (scheme 1
                        ).

After validating the feasibility of the proposed method, the experimental conditions, such as pH value and reaction time, were optimized through a series of tests to get high responses toward dopamine. First of all, buffers providing various pH were tried. Only minor enhancement was provided under acidic condition (citrate–phosphate buffers, Fig. S9). Better performances were obtained with Tris-HCl buffer system and pH 8.5 was found best suitable and adopted (Fig. 2
                        ). The kinetics of the reaction between dopamine and nanoclusters was explored next. It was found that the enhancement of Au-AgNCs fluorescence (F/F0) tended to be stable after 5 min incubation. 15 min here was adopted in order to ensure both full swing of reaction and the efficiency of the whole analytical process (Fig. 3
                        ).

In order to construct a relationship between dopamine and the fluorescence enhancement, samples at different concentrations were measured with the developed method under the optimized conditions. The extent of the fluorescence enhancement was found piecewise linear to the concentration of DA in the range of 0.01–1.7 μM and 1.7–10 μM (with linear correlation coefficient R2 0.99406 and 0.99927 respectively), the linear regression formula is F/F0 = 1.044 + 0.446 [DA] and F/F0 = 1.739 + 0.038 [DA] (Fig. 4
                        ), and the signal became nonlinear above 10 μM (Fig. S10). The limit of detection (LOD) was calculated to be 6.9 nmol·L-1 (three times the standard deviation of the background signal, 3σ). Confronted with previous reports for the same intention, the one we developed here was found to have prominent performances (Table 1
                        ). In a reproducibility study, seven replicate measurements of a DA sample at 0.8 μM gave a relative standard deviation (RSD) of 1.49%. This showed a good repeatability of this method.
